11
00:01:47,608 --> 00:01:49,441
   the cries of a newborn baby  

12
00:01:49,510 --> 00:01:51,743
          rang out from         
      sharecropper's cabin      

13
00:01:51,812 --> 00:01:55,080
     over the cotton fields     
    of the Mississippi Delta.   

14
00:01:55,149 --> 00:01:56,515
         [ Baby crying ]        

15
00:01:56,584 --> 00:01:58,283
     A boy was born that day    

16
00:01:58,352 --> 00:02:00,986
     that was going to make     
          a difference.         

17
00:02:01,055 --> 00:02:04,723
   His name -- Riley B. King.   

18
00:02:04,792 --> 00:02:08,093
       [ Thunder rumbles ]      

19
00:02:08,162 --> 00:02:09,895
             RAITT:             
  There's no music in the world 

20
00:02:09,964 --> 00:02:10,963
      that cuts emotionally     

21
00:02:11,031 --> 00:02:12,864
    the way that blues guitar   
            can cut.            

22
00:02:12,933 --> 00:02:15,367
 G. BENSON: When you say "blues"
    and you say "B.B. King,"    

23
00:02:15,436 --> 00:02:16,535
       you've said it all.      

24
00:02:16,604 --> 00:02:18,237
   That's the top of the line.  
           That's it.           

25
00:02:18,305 --> 00:02:23,275
 SANTANA: Sincere, honest, true,
     for real, and genuine.     

26
00:02:25,179 --> 00:02:27,112
       Those five things.       

27
00:02:27,181 --> 00:02:29,781
 If you have those five things, 
  then you can play the blues.  

28
00:02:29,850 --> 00:02:32,084
Otherwise, you're going to sound
         like a parakeet        

29
00:02:32,152 --> 00:02:34,219
       repeating something      
   that you don't understand.   

30
00:02:34,288 --> 00:02:35,821
 BONO: He's great in every way. 

31
00:02:35,889 --> 00:02:37,889
    Just the girth of the man   
            is great.           

32
00:02:37,958 --> 00:02:40,325
               ♪♪               

33
00:02:56,543 --> 00:02:57,843
       WILLIS: He's played      

34
00:02:57,911 --> 00:02:59,811
    probably in every country   
  where they have electricity,  

35
00:02:59,880 --> 00:03:02,681
      and probably a couple     
        where they don't.       

36
00:03:02,750 --> 00:03:05,350
    MAYER: B.B. King is gone    
       when he's playing.       

37
00:03:05,419 --> 00:03:09,321
      B.B. King's been gone     
   in the world of the blues,   

38
00:03:09,390 --> 00:03:12,491
    just living in that ether   
           for so long          

39
00:03:12,559 --> 00:03:14,659
     that he belongs to it.     

40
00:03:14,728 --> 00:03:16,762
               ♪♪               

41
00:03:16,830 --> 00:03:18,563
      [ Rhythmic clapping ]     

42
00:03:18,632 --> 00:03:19,965
           KING: Hey!           

43
00:03:20,034 --> 00:03:22,501
        [ Finale plays ]        

44
00:03:26,206 --> 00:03:27,773
     [ Cheers and applause ]    

45
00:03:27,841 --> 00:03:29,541
          [ Whistling ]         

46
00:03:29,610 --> 00:03:31,109
      Thank you very much.      

47
00:03:31,178 --> 00:03:35,981
           To be here           
  where somebody can truly say, 

48
00:03:36,050 --> 00:03:38,483
"B, this is where you were born.

49
00:03:38,552 --> 00:03:41,820
  This is where the world first 
  knew about you, right here,"  

50
00:03:41,889 --> 00:03:45,557
        is a high for me,       
    'cause I feel very good.    

51
00:03:45,626 --> 00:03:48,427
 My mother was named Nora Ella. 

52
00:03:48,495 --> 00:03:50,328
 My father was named Albert Lee.

53
00:03:50,397 --> 00:03:53,565
   But for a young couple that  
  hadn't been married too long  

54
00:03:53,634 --> 00:03:55,200
 and their first kid coming out,

55
00:03:55,269 --> 00:03:57,602
     they lived not too far     
         back over here.        

56
00:03:57,671 --> 00:04:01,807
And I believe my mother loved me
        and I loved her,        

57
00:04:01,875 --> 00:04:05,243
    and everything she tried    
 to teach me, I tried to learn. 

58
00:04:05,312 --> 00:04:10,849
      My mom left and moved     
   to Kilmichael, Mississippi.  

59
00:04:10,918 --> 00:04:17,622
I noticed that my mother had big
spots of blood clots in her eye.

60
00:04:17,691 --> 00:04:21,426
      She died of diabetes      
    the same as her son have,   

61
00:04:21,495 --> 00:04:23,261
            this one.           

62
00:04:24,631 --> 00:04:29,568
     I had been living with     
   other people all of my life  

63
00:04:29,636 --> 00:04:31,169
          since my mom.         

64
00:04:31,238 --> 00:04:34,339
          Their roots,          
     as they sometimes say,     

65
00:04:34,408 --> 00:04:38,043
      I think my beginning      
       was Elkhorn School.      

66
00:04:38,111 --> 00:04:39,377
          At that time,         

67
00:04:39,446 --> 00:04:42,681
       I had to walk about      
   five miles a day to school.  

68
00:04:42,749 --> 00:04:44,482
  MATTHEWS: Four months' school 

69
00:04:44,551 --> 00:04:47,352
 did not provide much education 
        on a plantation.        

70
00:04:47,421 --> 00:04:48,887
    He said, "I'm a big boy.    

71
00:04:48,956 --> 00:04:51,456
   I ought to be in the field,  
         not in school."        

72
00:04:51,525 --> 00:04:54,993
   KING: I was a regular hand   
from the time I was 7 years old.

73
00:04:55,062 --> 00:04:57,729
  See, they used to didn't have 
       no child labor laws      

74
00:04:57,798 --> 00:04:59,097
          and all that.         

75
00:04:59,166 --> 00:05:01,566
    So I was doing farm work    
    just like the adults was    

76
00:05:01,635 --> 00:05:02,934
        was when I was 7.       

77
00:05:03,003 --> 00:05:06,805
      I started about what      
  we call from "can to can't."  

78
00:05:06,874 --> 00:05:11,743
  "Can" means when you can see, 
  "can't" when you cannot see.  

79
00:05:11,812 --> 00:05:16,681
          ♪<i> Ooh, Lord,</i>          
  <i> ain't my troubles so hard</i> ♪  

80
00:05:16,750 --> 00:05:21,052
          ♪<i> Ooh, Lord,</i>          
     <i> my troubles so hard</i> ♪     

81
00:05:21,121 --> 00:05:24,556
MATTHEWS: Out of that condition,
      the blues were born.      

82
00:05:24,625 --> 00:05:28,727
      KING: Usually one guy     
  would be plowing by himself,  

83
00:05:28,795 --> 00:05:34,466
        or maybe one guy        
       would take his hoe       

84
00:05:34,534 --> 00:05:38,870
        and chop way out        
   in front of everybody else.  

85
00:05:38,939 --> 00:05:41,606
          And usually,          
  you would hear this guy sing. 

86
00:05:41,675 --> 00:05:44,342
               ♪♪               

87
00:05:44,411 --> 00:05:48,980
♪ Oh, I wake up in the morning ♪

88
00:05:49,049 --> 00:05:50,348
   BLAND: That's the only time  

89
00:05:50,417 --> 00:05:52,217
       you'd get a chance       
        to sing the blues       

90
00:05:52,286 --> 00:05:53,551
       is out in the field      

91
00:05:53,620 --> 00:05:56,321
   because your parents didn't  
    allow that in the house.    

92
00:05:56,390 --> 00:05:58,323
     Nothing but spirituals.    

93
00:05:58,392 --> 00:05:59,891
  So if you're picking cotton,  

94
00:05:59,960 --> 00:06:02,494
      you can sing whatever     
   you want to sing, you know?  

95
00:06:02,562 --> 00:06:04,429
   FREEMAN: To play that music  

96
00:06:04,498 --> 00:06:07,899
     and not invoke the name    
    of Jesus or God, I guess,   

97
00:06:07,968 --> 00:06:11,102
   then who are you invoking?   

98
00:06:11,171 --> 00:06:13,038
           The Devil.           

99
00:06:13,106 --> 00:06:14,906
     TROUT: A lot of people     
         in the church,         

100
00:06:14,975 --> 00:06:17,509
   they go through this thing   
  that it's the Devil's music,  

101
00:06:17,577 --> 00:06:22,380
      but the way he plays      
      and the way he sings,     

102
00:06:22,449 --> 00:06:24,582
    that is a gift from God.    

103
00:06:24,651 --> 00:06:26,785
And if you are at all religious,

104
00:06:26,853 --> 00:06:29,521
        you will believe        
      that he has that gift     

105
00:06:29,589 --> 00:06:34,092
  and that he was touched when  
 he was, you know, in the womb. 

106
00:06:34,161 --> 00:06:36,661
FAIR: When he joined the church,
  well, Archie was a preacher.  

107
00:06:36,730 --> 00:06:38,263
        My brother-in-law       
         was a preacher.        

108
00:06:38,331 --> 00:06:40,131
   He preached his church out.  

109
00:06:40,200 --> 00:06:42,067
   KING: Reverend Archie Fair   
         was our pastor         

110
00:06:42,135 --> 00:06:44,736
   and the first person I ever  
   heard play electric guitar,  

111
00:06:44,805 --> 00:06:46,805
         and that's why         
    I wanted to be like him.    

112
00:06:46,873 --> 00:06:50,241
      FAIR: In the church,      
   this boy would get a chance  

113
00:06:50,310 --> 00:06:53,011
   to play on Archie's guitar   
            a little.           

114
00:06:53,080 --> 00:06:54,345
      KING: This preacher,      

115
00:06:54,414 --> 00:06:56,614
          after church          
     on a Sunday afternoon,     

116
00:06:56,683 --> 00:06:58,817
     would visit his sister,    
       which was my aunt.       

117
00:06:58,885 --> 00:07:01,619
 And he'd always lay this guitar
           on the bed,          

118
00:07:01,688 --> 00:07:04,522
    and I'd go get it as soon   
   as they turned their backs.  

119
00:07:04,591 --> 00:07:05,890
       So I think this is       

120
00:07:05,959 --> 00:07:08,426
     really what started me     
   to fooling with the guitar,  

121
00:07:08,495 --> 00:07:11,096
        not by listening        
  to some of the other people.  

122
00:07:11,164 --> 00:07:14,432
He was a preacher and a teacher,

123
00:07:14,501 --> 00:07:18,136
 and I liked him, worshiped him.

124
00:07:18,205 --> 00:07:20,271
               ♪♪               

125
00:07:20,340 --> 00:07:21,673
    When my grandmother died,   

126
00:07:21,741 --> 00:07:23,641
         I still stayed         
       in the little house      

127
00:07:23,710 --> 00:07:27,245
    that my grandmother and I   
  had lived in before she died. 

128
00:07:27,314 --> 00:07:30,048
        I felt deserted.        

129
00:07:30,117 --> 00:07:33,685
         Nobody but me.         

130
00:07:33,753 --> 00:07:35,320
         And I remember         

131
00:07:35,388 --> 00:07:38,122
  she owed something like $35,  
        $40 or something,       

132
00:07:38,191 --> 00:07:39,958
 but we didn't make much money. 

133
00:07:40,026 --> 00:07:41,893
 I was making $15 a month, so...

134
00:07:41,962 --> 00:07:44,262
           But I paid           
     my grandmother's bill.     

135
00:07:44,331 --> 00:07:46,564
      I paid it off myself.     

136
00:07:46,633 --> 00:07:47,765
      After my daddy got me     

137
00:07:49,669 --> 00:07:52,937
         and brought me         
   to Lexington, Mississippi,   

138
00:07:53,006 --> 00:07:55,073
       and I started going      
        to school there,        

139
00:07:55,141 --> 00:07:57,709
 which was the first big school 
        I'd ever gone to.       

140
00:07:57,777 --> 00:07:59,978
  He had three girls and a boy, 

141
00:08:00,046 --> 00:08:03,615
    and those was my sisters    
          and brother.          

142
00:08:03,683 --> 00:08:06,184
     My daddy never told me     
          he loved me.          

143
00:08:06,253 --> 00:08:07,519
           Never did.           

144
00:08:07,587 --> 00:08:10,889
But anytime he was very pleased,
       I had that feeling.      

145
00:08:10,957 --> 00:08:13,892
       He called me "Jack"      
   out of the clear blue sky.   

146
00:08:13,960 --> 00:08:15,660
    "Jack, what do you think    
          about this?"          

147
00:08:15,729 --> 00:08:17,295
      Or "What do you think     
          about that?"          

148
00:08:17,364 --> 00:08:19,497
      And I'd feel so good      
      till I'd almost cry,      

149
00:08:19,566 --> 00:08:21,099
 'cause I knew what that meant. 

150
00:08:23,470 --> 00:08:27,538
    MATTHEWS: In those days,    
       it was oppression,       

151
00:08:27,607 --> 00:08:31,309
     and you'd be depressed     
        by the oppression       

152
00:08:31,378 --> 00:08:33,912
   because you had no rights.   

153
00:08:33,980 --> 00:08:35,546
    Black folk had no rights.   

154
00:08:35,615 --> 00:08:38,283
    You were not black then.    
  You were Negroes or niggers.  

155
00:08:38,351 --> 00:08:40,952
               ♪♪               

156
00:08:41,021 --> 00:08:42,487
    KING: ♪ But to know me ♪    

157
00:08:42,555 --> 00:08:45,089
 And for you that don't know it,
      this citizen council,     

158
00:08:45,158 --> 00:08:46,891
    White Citizens' Council,    

159
00:08:46,960 --> 00:08:48,526
       began in Indianola,      
         Mississippi --         

160
00:08:48,595 --> 00:08:51,996
            my home.            

161
00:08:52,065 --> 00:08:57,936
  HENSON: Our place was to work 
  hard and obey the white man.  

162
00:08:58,004 --> 00:09:00,204
              KING:             
  That was one of my first days 

163
00:09:00,273 --> 00:09:03,541
   of really experiencing what  
  segregation was really like.  

164
00:09:03,610 --> 00:09:06,944
     A mob had killed a boy.    
        They'd hung him.        

165
00:09:07,013 --> 00:09:09,781
 It had to do with a white lady,
            you know.           

166
00:09:09,849 --> 00:09:13,351
     They had castrated him     
    and drug him behind a car   

167
00:09:13,420 --> 00:09:17,422
 to the courthouse in Lexington,
    Mississippi -- Lexington.   

168
00:09:17,490 --> 00:09:19,657
          And I saw it.         

169
00:09:19,726 --> 00:09:22,627
      And that's something      
 I've never forgotten, I guess, 

170
00:09:22,696 --> 00:09:24,829
   It's something like seeing   
    people killed in the war.   

171
00:09:24,898 --> 00:09:27,031
      You don't forget it.      

172
00:09:27,100 --> 00:09:30,468
MATTHEWS: You were just a thing,
       not a human being,       

173
00:09:30,537 --> 00:09:31,669
       just a work thing.       

174
00:09:31,738 --> 00:09:32,904
       They had a slogan,       

175
00:09:32,972 --> 00:09:35,807
         "If a mule die,        
        buy another one."       

176
00:09:35,875 --> 00:09:38,209
      KING: "Kill a nigger,     
       hire another one,"       

177
00:09:38,278 --> 00:09:40,211
       and that's the way       
        I was brought up.       

178
00:09:40,280 --> 00:09:42,380
    MATTHEWS: And that meant    
        you were nobody.        

179
00:09:42,449 --> 00:09:44,615
 You just about equal to a mule.

180
00:09:44,684 --> 00:09:49,187
     It was badder than bad.    

181
00:09:49,255 --> 00:09:51,889
   EVERS: We all were subject   
      to racism and bigotry     

182
00:09:51,958 --> 00:09:53,591
     and hatred and denial.     

183
00:09:53,660 --> 00:09:55,159
        None of us could        
      get a drink of water      

184
00:09:55,228 --> 00:09:56,994
   at a public water fountain.  

185
00:09:57,063 --> 00:09:59,931
 So yes, he faced the same thing
      that all of us faced.     

186
00:09:59,999 --> 00:10:03,634
   There was racism, bigotry,   
           and hatred.          

187
00:10:03,703 --> 00:10:05,136
  But let me add this, though.  

188
00:10:05,205 --> 00:10:06,904
     Let me say this to you     
           about B.B.           

189
00:10:06,973 --> 00:10:09,173
   He never let that turn him   
      against white people.     

190
00:10:09,242 --> 00:10:11,242
    FREEMAN: Young Riley King   

191
00:10:11,311 --> 00:10:14,445
    started dreaming of life    
       back in the Delta.       

192
00:10:14,514 --> 00:10:16,647
       The Delta was home.      

193
00:10:16,716 --> 00:10:18,082
        So late in 1941,        

194
00:10:18,151 --> 00:10:21,152
        16-year-old Riley       
      jumped on his bicycle     

195
00:10:21,221 --> 00:10:24,489
and began to pedal his way home,

196
00:10:24,557 --> 00:10:26,657
          back to where         
       his heart belonged.      

197
00:10:26,726 --> 00:10:31,329
               ♪♪               

198
00:10:31,397 --> 00:10:34,599
          KING: I came          
   to the Barrett Plantation.   

199
00:10:34,667 --> 00:10:36,334
        So what he did --       

200
00:10:36,402 --> 00:10:40,705
    he hired a black overseer   
       named Mr. Baggett,       

201
00:10:40,773 --> 00:10:42,573
         Booker Baggett.        

202
00:10:42,642 --> 00:10:46,110
    And we worked like crazy    
 because we wanted to keep him. 

203
00:10:46,179 --> 00:10:50,248
 And Mr. Baggett is the one that
  taught me to drive tractors.  

204
00:10:50,316 --> 00:10:53,151
 Then is the time that I decided
    I wanted to get married,    

205
00:10:53,219 --> 00:10:55,153
        and I got married       
        to a young lady.        

206
00:10:55,221 --> 00:10:56,921
     DAVIS: To Martha King.     

207
00:10:56,990 --> 00:11:00,525
          In that year,         
  we lived in a house together. 

208
00:11:00,593 --> 00:11:04,395
    We lived in a three-room    
         shotgun house.         

209
00:11:04,464 --> 00:11:07,265
     Two doors, one in front    
        and one in back.        

210
00:11:07,333 --> 00:11:09,400
   KING: Saturdays was my day.  

211
00:11:09,469 --> 00:11:12,603
     Go to town on Saturdays    
      and have a good time.     

212
00:11:12,672 --> 00:11:14,305
  CLAY: People were in and out, 

213
00:11:14,374 --> 00:11:17,441
 gambling and doing what little 
    dancing they were doing.    

214
00:11:17,510 --> 00:11:18,843
        If you didn't get       
        on Church Street,       

215
00:11:18,912 --> 00:11:20,545
  you wouldn't be in Indianola. 

216
00:11:20,613 --> 00:11:22,213
   KING: I came in in a hurry   

217
00:11:22,282 --> 00:11:24,982
   on my way to go to a church  
       to sing that night.      

218
00:11:25,051 --> 00:11:28,452
        I'd been plowing,       
        plowing, plowing,       

219
00:11:28,521 --> 00:11:29,854
      and then it happened.     

220
00:11:29,923 --> 00:11:31,522
    We got off that evening.    

221
00:11:31,591 --> 00:11:35,893
     I cut this ignition off    
         of the tractor,        

222
00:11:35,962 --> 00:11:39,430
   and I jumped down and start  
 running to get ready to go out,

223
00:11:39,499 --> 00:11:42,300
    and it started up again.    

224
00:11:42,368 --> 00:11:44,235
      And when the tractor      
        started up again,       

225
00:11:44,304 --> 00:11:46,370
        it went forward,        

226
00:11:46,439 --> 00:11:48,806
   and all of this broke off.   

227
00:11:48,875 --> 00:11:51,642
    Scared me half to death.    

228
00:11:51,711 --> 00:11:53,744
    I never did stop running,   

229
00:11:53,813 --> 00:11:56,948
    and that's the first time   
       I went to Memphis.       

230
00:11:57,016 --> 00:12:00,585
       ♪<i> And I'm walkin'</i> ♪      

231
00:12:00,653 --> 00:12:02,820
     ♪<i> Walkin' and cryin'</i> ♪     

232
00:12:02,889 --> 00:12:04,422
     When I came to Memphis     

233
00:12:04,490 --> 00:12:07,692
       and started hearing      
   all those other guys play,   

234
00:12:07,760 --> 00:12:10,494
  I found out I wasn't nothing. 

235
00:12:10,563 --> 00:12:12,830
           That much.           

236
00:12:12,899 --> 00:12:15,466
   I'm still like that today.   

237
00:12:15,535 --> 00:12:18,636
 WHITE: ♪ Dead from your eyes ♪ 

238
00:12:18,705 --> 00:12:20,471
    FREEMAN: Once in Memphis,   

239
00:12:20,540 --> 00:12:23,140
        B.B. King sought        
      and found his cousin,     

240
00:12:23,209 --> 00:12:27,078
 the great bluesman Bukka White.

241
00:12:27,146 --> 00:12:30,381
 KING: Bukka was born up around 
    West Point, Mississippi,    

242
00:12:30,450 --> 00:12:33,417
     and a lot of people say    
      he taught me to play,     

243
00:12:33,486 --> 00:12:34,952
      but that's not true.      

244
00:12:35,021 --> 00:12:39,457
 But he did teach me quite a bit
   about being a blues player.  

245
00:12:39,525 --> 00:12:42,526
   Bukka White used to tell me  
   that to be a blues singer,   

246
00:12:42,595 --> 00:12:44,595
     you should always dress    

247
00:12:44,664 --> 00:12:47,565
    like you was trying to go   
  to the bank to borrow money.  

248
00:12:47,633 --> 00:12:49,200
    Which means you dressed,    

249
00:12:49,268 --> 00:12:52,737
   well, a word musicians use,  
    kind of sharp, you know.    

250
00:12:52,805 --> 00:12:56,073
       And he used to play      
   with a slide on his finger.  

251
00:12:56,142 --> 00:12:58,275
   And I could never get that.  

252
00:12:58,344 --> 00:13:01,312
    I've got stupid fingers.    
    They just wouldn't work.    

253
00:13:01,381 --> 00:13:06,684
   So in order to get somewhat  
   the type sound that he had,  

254
00:13:06,753 --> 00:13:10,888
     I would trill my hand,     
           like that.           

255
00:13:10,957 --> 00:13:14,425
   And I think over the years,  
 I've done pretty good with it. 

256
00:13:14,494 --> 00:13:16,527
  I still don't have it right.  

257
00:13:16,596 --> 00:13:19,563
        I stayed up there       
 for about six to eight months, 

258
00:13:19,632 --> 00:13:24,869
and then I called some of family
        back and I said,        

259
00:13:24,937 --> 00:13:27,838
  "Tell Mr. Barrett I'm sorry.  

260
00:13:27,907 --> 00:13:31,075
    And I would like to work    
        and pay it off."        

261
00:13:31,144 --> 00:13:34,545
     Well, with wobbly legs,    
          I came back,          

262
00:13:34,614 --> 00:13:37,448
           and I think          
    it cost me $500 or $600,    

263
00:13:37,517 --> 00:13:38,983
       and I paid it off.       

264
00:13:39,051 --> 00:13:42,686
 And the next time I left to go 
 to Memphis to start my career, 

265
00:13:42,755 --> 00:13:45,923
     I started it correctly.    

266
00:13:45,992 --> 00:13:47,892
         ♪<i> Whoa, Lord</i> ♪         

267
00:13:47,960 --> 00:13:49,960
    ♪<i> What a beautiful city</i> ♪   

268
00:13:50,029 --> 00:13:52,963
  ♪<i> Oh, what a beautiful city</i> ♪ 

269
00:13:53,032 --> 00:13:54,965
               ♪♪               

270
00:13:55,034 --> 00:13:58,536
    When we left Mississippi    
        going to Memphis,       

271
00:13:58,604 --> 00:14:02,339
  we expected many, many things 
     to happen, and it did.     

272
00:14:02,408 --> 00:14:05,376
       The late Sonny Boy,      
the second Sonny Boy Williamson,

273
00:14:05,444 --> 00:14:07,545
       he was on the radio      
   in West Memphis, Arkansas.   

274
00:14:07,547 --> 00:14:09,947
    I decided I wanted to go    
      and see him one day,      

275
00:14:09,949 --> 00:14:12,183
       and one day I did.       

276
00:14:12,185 --> 00:14:14,385
And when I went over to see him,

277
00:14:14,387 --> 00:14:16,554
          I begged him          
      to let me sing a song     

278
00:14:16,556 --> 00:14:18,756
     So he made me audition,    
           and I did,           

279
00:14:18,758 --> 00:14:19,924
        and he liked it,        

280
00:14:19,926 --> 00:14:22,326
          and he put me         
      on the show that day.     

281
00:14:22,328 --> 00:14:25,129
         And that night,        
    he had two jobs to play.    

282
00:14:25,131 --> 00:14:26,564
   One of them he didn't want   

283
00:14:26,566 --> 00:14:28,499
      because it didn't pay     
           much money.          

284
00:14:28,501 --> 00:14:30,267
      So he called the lady     

285
00:14:30,269 --> 00:14:32,303
     and asked the lady that    
  he was supposed to play for,  

286
00:14:32,305 --> 00:14:33,637
    did she hear the program?   

287
00:14:33,639 --> 00:14:34,939
          She said yes.         

288
00:14:34,941 --> 00:14:37,508
   So I went over there, man,   
     and they paid me $12 --    

289
00:14:37,510 --> 00:14:39,310
      12 American dollars.      

290
00:14:39,312 --> 00:14:41,445
That's a lot of bread, you know,

291
00:14:41,447 --> 00:14:45,082
 for a guy that had been making 
     like 35 cents a hundred    

292
00:14:45,084 --> 00:14:46,450
    picking cotton, you know?   

293
00:14:46,452 --> 00:14:49,620
 She said, "If you can get a job
          on the radio,         

294
00:14:49,622 --> 00:14:53,290
       like Sonny Boy has,      
     I'll give you this job,    

295
00:14:53,292 --> 00:14:56,360
        and you can play        
       six nights a week."      

296
00:14:56,362 --> 00:14:58,028
    And I thought about that    
            and said,           

297
00:14:58,030 --> 00:15:00,764
    "God, I hope I can get me   
     in a job on the radio."    

298
00:15:00,766 --> 00:15:04,735
               ♪♪               

299
00:15:04,737 --> 00:15:07,271
 Well, I'm just a blues singer, 

300
00:15:07,273 --> 00:15:12,042
        a tractor driver,       
         a truck driver.        

301
00:15:12,111 --> 00:15:14,078
I was a disc jockey for a while.

302
00:15:14,146 --> 00:15:17,314
        I sing the blues        
       because I lived it.      

303
00:15:17,383 --> 00:15:18,949
   You're probably wondering,   
           "That guy,           

304
00:15:19,018 --> 00:15:20,718
        the way you talk,       
     you're a disc jockey?"     

305
00:15:20,786 --> 00:15:24,288
            Trust me.           
   I was for about five years.  

306
00:15:24,357 --> 00:15:28,726
    This is B.B. King making    
 a statement and a natural fact.

307
00:15:28,794 --> 00:15:31,295
              WDIA.             

308
00:15:31,364 --> 00:15:33,797
     Everybody want to know     
      why I sing the blues.     

309
00:15:33,866 --> 00:15:37,935
  The first all-black operated  
    station in the Mid South,   

310
00:15:38,004 --> 00:15:40,671
 in fact, I think in the nation.

311
00:15:40,740 --> 00:15:44,642
        [ Radio tuning ]        

312
00:15:44,710 --> 00:15:47,378
      THOMAS: It's a good,      
       good morning to you      

313
00:15:47,446 --> 00:15:51,682
    on an all-blues Saturday    
          here on WDIA          

314
00:15:51,751 --> 00:15:54,518
     with your Rufus Thomas.    

315
00:15:54,587 --> 00:15:58,689
  KING: This new radio station  
  was being opened in Memphis,  

316
00:15:58,758 --> 00:16:00,891
      so when the red light     
        went off the air        

317
00:16:00,960 --> 00:16:03,060
      I went to the window      
         and I knocked.         

318
00:16:03,129 --> 00:16:05,262
So he came to the door and said,

319
00:16:05,331 --> 00:16:07,564
     "What can I do for you,    
          young fella?"         

320
00:16:07,633 --> 00:16:09,633
       And I said, 'Well,       
     I want to make a record    

321
00:16:09,702 --> 00:16:12,403
and I want to go on the radio,'"
         and he laughed.        

322
00:16:12,471 --> 00:16:15,839
     And Mr. Ferguson said,     
 "Well, we don't make records," 

323
00:16:15,841 --> 00:16:18,208
         and then he had        
        this deep look --       

324
00:16:18,210 --> 00:16:21,045
    thought look on his face.   

325
00:16:21,047 --> 00:16:23,313
  And he said to Mr. Williams,  
            he said,            

326
00:16:23,315 --> 00:16:24,982
      "You know, we've got      
       this new product."       

327
00:16:24,984 --> 00:16:28,218
He said, "Maybe he would be good
     for this new product."     

328
00:16:28,287 --> 00:16:30,687
 So he went and got me a bottle,

329
00:16:30,756 --> 00:16:33,090
  and he held it up like this.  

330
00:16:33,159 --> 00:16:36,760
  He said, "This is Pep-Ti-Kon. 

331
00:16:36,829 --> 00:16:40,030
  Do you think you could write  
        a jingle for it?"       

332
00:16:40,099 --> 00:16:41,965
 I started to thinking about it,

333
00:16:42,034 --> 00:16:44,268
     and I said, "Yes, sir,     
     I can write a jingle."     

334
00:16:44,336 --> 00:16:46,537
      So it went like this.     

335
00:16:46,605 --> 00:16:49,072
   ♪ Pep-Ti-Kon sure is good ♪  

336
00:16:49,141 --> 00:16:51,175
   ♪ Pep-Ti-Kon sure is good ♪  

337
00:16:51,243 --> 00:16:53,043
   ♪ Pep-Ti-Kon sure is good ♪  

338
00:16:53,112 --> 00:16:55,279
    ♪ You can get it anywhere   
     in your neighborhood ♪     

339
00:16:55,347 --> 00:16:56,580
    He said, "You're hired."    

340
00:16:56,649 --> 00:16:57,781
           [ Laughs ]           

341
00:16:57,850 --> 00:16:59,883
               ♪♪               

342
00:17:04,557 --> 00:17:06,123
      MAN: Blues Boy King.      

343
00:17:06,192 --> 00:17:07,791
        Blues Boy, who --       
   Did your dad name you that?  

344
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:10,961
     KING: No, I used to be     
    a disc jockey in Memphis,   

345
00:17:11,030 --> 00:17:14,031
 and they called me the Boy from
  Beale Street, the Blues Boy.  

346
00:17:14,099 --> 00:17:16,400
           So people,           
  instead of saying Blues Boy,  

347
00:17:16,468 --> 00:17:18,802
     they just started using    
        the word "B.B.,"        

348
00:17:18,871 --> 00:17:20,671
     which meant Blues Boy.     

349
00:17:20,739 --> 00:17:24,007
       And my real name is      
         Riley B. King.         

350
00:17:24,076 --> 00:17:26,810
 Now most times if someone would
  come up and say, "Hi, Riley," 

351
00:17:26,879 --> 00:17:28,812
         I would wonder         
    who they're taking about.   

352
00:17:28,881 --> 00:17:31,582
            LOCKWOOD:           
 I taught him the best I could. 

353
00:17:31,650 --> 00:17:32,850
         A lot of times         

354
00:17:32,918 --> 00:17:35,118
      he didn't understand      
     what I was telling him,    

355
00:17:35,187 --> 00:17:37,254
 But when I put him with a group

356
00:17:37,323 --> 00:17:40,490
    that put pressure on him    
      and he had to learn.      

357
00:17:42,995 --> 00:17:45,562
   You can't work with nobody   
      without you knowing.      

358
00:17:47,166 --> 00:17:49,032
You see where the bass player is
            right now           

359
00:17:49,101 --> 00:17:50,200
   when you see B.B. playing?   

360
00:17:50,269 --> 00:17:52,636
        The bass player's       
        right behind him.       

361
00:17:52,705 --> 00:17:55,272
   That's what he listens to.   

362
00:17:55,341 --> 00:17:57,174
          Now you know.         

363
00:17:57,243 --> 00:17:58,642
   KING: In fact, it's like --  

364
00:17:58,711 --> 00:18:01,178
     I usually tell the band    
      like I have today --      

365
00:18:01,247 --> 00:18:03,747
 "You know a lot more than I do 

366
00:18:03,816 --> 00:18:05,916
 and you play better than I do, 

367
00:18:05,985 --> 00:18:08,085
    but I'm the band leader."   

368
00:18:08,153 --> 00:18:10,187
       LOCKWOOD.: B.B. was      
   just learning how to play,   

369
00:18:10,256 --> 00:18:12,289
    but he always could sing    

370
00:18:12,358 --> 00:18:14,124
     and he finally learned     
          how to play.          

371
00:18:14,193 --> 00:18:16,326
       RAITT: You can look      
       at B.B. King's life      

372
00:18:16,395 --> 00:18:19,329
     and listen to his music    
from the beginning until the end

373
00:18:19,398 --> 00:18:23,000
        and in one career       
   and one man's contribution,  

374
00:18:23,068 --> 00:18:25,302
       you can really have      
      the whole ball of wax     

375
00:18:25,371 --> 00:18:27,938
       of what's important      
      and what will endure,     

376
00:18:28,007 --> 00:18:31,008
   because there's no records   
          more seminal          

377
00:18:31,076 --> 00:18:34,177
        than B.B. King's        
     important contribution     

378
00:18:34,246 --> 00:18:35,979
       as a guitar player       
         and as a singer        

379
00:18:36,048 --> 00:18:38,548
     and those records have     
 always stood the test of time. 

380
00:18:38,617 --> 00:18:40,784
               ♪♪               

381
00:18:40,853 --> 00:18:43,053
     MAN: I've always wanted    
         to meet Helen.         

382
00:18:43,122 --> 00:18:45,222
    KING: Helen? Who's Helen?   

383
00:18:45,291 --> 00:18:47,424
       MAN: Helen, Helen,       
   uh, your guitar, you know.   

384
00:18:47,493 --> 00:18:48,925
    When you start playing --   

385
00:18:48,994 --> 00:18:50,460
 KING: Oh, you're talking about 
            Lucille?            

386
00:18:50,529 --> 00:18:51,762
        This is Lucille.        
         That's my baby.        

387
00:18:51,830 --> 00:18:54,164
          [ Laughter ]          

388
00:18:54,233 --> 00:18:56,933
MAN: That's not the guitar I saw
    you with last night, B.B.   

389
00:18:57,002 --> 00:19:00,537
          [ Laughter ]          

390
00:19:00,606 --> 00:19:03,740
       KING: The first one      
     that was named Lucille     

391
00:19:03,809 --> 00:19:08,278
     was because of a fight     
     in a little night club.    

392
00:19:08,347 --> 00:19:10,847
   So, this particular night,   
    two guys started to fight   

393
00:19:10,916 --> 00:19:13,884
   and one of them knocked the  
other one over on this container

394
00:19:13,952 --> 00:19:16,053
          and the fuel          
      spilled on the floor      

395
00:19:16,121 --> 00:19:19,322
   and it was already burning,  
  so they tried to put it out.  

396
00:19:19,391 --> 00:19:21,925
     It seemed to burn more.    

397
00:19:21,994 --> 00:19:24,428
  Everybody in the little club  
        that was dancing        

398
00:19:24,496 --> 00:19:27,297
     started to run outside,    
          including me.         

399
00:19:27,366 --> 00:19:29,099
 But when I got on the outside, 

400
00:19:29,168 --> 00:19:32,002
 I remembered that I had ran off
       and left my guitar.      

401
00:19:32,071 --> 00:19:34,271
    So I started back for it    

402
00:19:34,339 --> 00:19:36,039
      and the fellas there      
 that were working with me said,

403
00:19:36,108 --> 00:19:37,074
       "No, don't to it."       

404
00:19:37,142 --> 00:19:38,341
       But I went anyway.       

405
00:19:38,410 --> 00:19:39,643
      And I got my guitar,      

406
00:19:39,711 --> 00:19:42,446
but I was almost burned to death
       trying to save it.       

407
00:19:42,514 --> 00:19:43,747
      So the next morning,      

408
00:19:43,816 --> 00:19:46,183
      we found that two men     
       had gotten burned,       

409
00:19:46,251 --> 00:19:49,152
  got trapped in the building,  
      got burned to death.      

410
00:19:49,221 --> 00:19:52,289
And we also found that these two
 guys was fighting about a lady.

411
00:19:52,357 --> 00:19:54,825
  The lady's name was Lucille.  

412
00:19:54,893 --> 00:19:56,259
   I named the guitar Lucille   

413
00:19:56,328 --> 00:19:58,795
     to remind me not to do     
    a thing like that again,    

414
00:19:58,864 --> 00:20:00,363
         and I haven't.         

415
00:20:00,432 --> 00:20:01,731
           [ Laughs ]           

416
00:20:03,702 --> 00:20:07,337
        ♪<i> Now, darling</i> ♪        

417
00:20:07,406 --> 00:20:10,674
     ♪<i> You know I love you</i> ♪    

418
00:20:10,742 --> 00:20:13,477
      FREEMAN: Beale Street     
    entrepreneur Robert Henry   

419
00:20:13,545 --> 00:20:16,480
      started to look after     
   the interests of B.B. King.  

420
00:20:16,548 --> 00:20:18,515
This resulted in a national tour

421
00:20:18,584 --> 00:20:20,884
   of the main black theaters   
           and clubs,           

422
00:20:20,953 --> 00:20:23,954
 known as the Chitlin' Circuit. 

423
00:20:24,022 --> 00:20:26,923
      The road was no place     
         for a marriage.        

424
00:20:26,992 --> 00:20:32,529
            The road            
    was B.B. King's new home.   

425
00:20:32,598 --> 00:20:35,131
   DAVIS: And he called me and  
  said, "'Cile," I said, "Yes?" 

426
00:20:35,200 --> 00:20:36,766
He said "Martha's done left me."

427
00:20:36,835 --> 00:20:39,736
I said, "Girl, why you leaving?"

428
00:20:39,805 --> 00:20:42,172
          And she said,         
 "'Cause he won't stay at home. 

429
00:20:42,241 --> 00:20:44,140
He playing -- going everywhere."

430
00:20:44,209 --> 00:20:45,809
    I said, "Girl, you crazy.   

431
00:20:45,878 --> 00:20:48,144
         You should stay        
       with your husband."      

432
00:20:48,213 --> 00:20:50,247
         But she didn't.        

433
00:20:50,315 --> 00:20:54,384
      OWENS: This business      
  is a very difficult business, 

434
00:20:54,453 --> 00:20:58,421
 but I couldn't live without it 

435
00:20:58,490 --> 00:21:02,192
   and I don't think he could   
    live without it, either.    

436
00:21:02,261 --> 00:21:05,962
 ♪<i> Oh, gone and left me, baby</i> ♪ 

437
00:21:06,031 --> 00:21:14,137
      ♪<i> For someone else</i> ♪      

438
00:21:15,274 --> 00:21:16,840
  KING: A little bit later on,  

439
00:21:16,909 --> 00:21:19,075
    after I had been touring    
          for a while,          

440
00:21:19,144 --> 00:21:23,413
  then I turned the disc jockey 
     loose and just toured.     

441
00:21:23,482 --> 00:21:25,448
    And I'm still doing that.   

442
00:21:25,517 --> 00:21:28,551
               ♪♪               

443
00:21:28,620 --> 00:21:31,655
P. WALKER: At the time when B.B.
       got his first bus,       

444
00:21:31,723 --> 00:21:33,523
      there was excitement      

445
00:21:33,592 --> 00:21:35,859
       because coming out       
       of a station wagon       

446
00:21:35,928 --> 00:21:38,929
           into a big           
    Continental Trailway bus    

447
00:21:38,997 --> 00:21:41,398
    was just a marvelous feat   
         for the group.         

448
00:21:41,466 --> 00:21:42,899
      And it was something      

449
00:21:42,968 --> 00:21:45,769
  that none of the other groups 
          had, either.          

450
00:21:45,837 --> 00:21:48,138
            WITHERS:            
  This is the original picture  

451
00:21:48,206 --> 00:21:52,642
      of the B.B. King Band     
    on Beale Street in 1955.    

452
00:21:52,711 --> 00:21:55,445
       C. WALKER: I think       
    everybody knows this band   

453
00:21:55,514 --> 00:21:57,580
     as the B.B. King Band.     

454
00:21:57,649 --> 00:21:59,149
    This the B.B. King Band.    

455
00:21:59,217 --> 00:22:01,084
    No matter how many bands    
        he goes through,        

456
00:22:01,153 --> 00:22:03,787
       this will always be      
       the B.B. King Band.      

457
00:22:03,855 --> 00:22:04,988
       OWENS: We were bad.      

458
00:22:05,057 --> 00:22:06,156
          [ Laughter ]          

459
00:22:06,224 --> 00:22:07,557
       Yeah, we were good.      

460
00:22:07,626 --> 00:22:12,362
          On the seat,          
  you would have a box of food  

461
00:22:12,431 --> 00:22:15,365
       like pork and beans      
    and sardines and crackers   

462
00:22:15,434 --> 00:22:17,000
     and that kind of stuff,    

463
00:22:17,069 --> 00:22:20,170
     because a lot of times     
     you wouldn't have time     

464
00:22:20,238 --> 00:22:23,740
     to eat at a restaurant     
        or café, per se.        

465
00:22:23,809 --> 00:22:26,109
    And it was very difficult   

466
00:22:26,178 --> 00:22:30,847
   because a lot of the places  
   you couldn't go in anyway.   

467
00:22:30,916 --> 00:22:36,720
     MARTIN LUTHER KING JR.:    
And I've seen the Promised Land.

468
00:22:36,788 --> 00:22:40,023
  I may not get there with you, 

469
00:22:40,092 --> 00:22:42,826
 but I want you to know tonight 

470
00:22:42,894 --> 00:22:47,297
      that we, as a people,     
 will get to the Promised Land. 

471
00:22:47,365 --> 00:22:49,566
            WITHERS:            
    Desegregation of America    

472
00:22:49,634 --> 00:22:52,368
  didn't start until the '60s,  

473
00:22:52,437 --> 00:22:54,370
   and B.B. had been on a roll  

474
00:22:54,439 --> 00:22:57,073
     for a good 10, 12 years    
          before that.          

475
00:22:57,142 --> 00:22:59,242
             OWENS:             
  We just played everywhere --  

476
00:22:59,311 --> 00:23:02,312
         Apollo Theater         
    to the honky-tonk joints,   

477
00:23:02,380 --> 00:23:04,280
      all over the country.     

478
00:23:04,349 --> 00:23:06,049
              GUY:              
 Well, B was always on the road.

479
00:23:06,118 --> 00:23:07,484
  He's the only guy, I think -- 

480
00:23:07,552 --> 00:23:12,122
     I think he had a record    
that he plays 365 days one year.

481
00:23:12,190 --> 00:23:14,724
 And I'd tell him all the time, 
   "I don't want that record."  

482
00:23:14,793 --> 00:23:15,725
      He can keep that one.     

483
00:23:15,794 --> 00:23:17,060
            You know?           

484
00:23:17,129 --> 00:23:20,196
    DR. JOHN: I used to work    
      like 320 days a year.     

485
00:23:20,265 --> 00:23:21,764
     B.B. worked more gigs.     

486
00:23:21,833 --> 00:23:24,434
    OWENS: I don't know where   
    he gets the energy from.    

487
00:23:24,503 --> 00:23:28,371
        I mean, this man        
     works more than anybody    

488
00:23:28,440 --> 00:23:31,241
  because the road is his home. 

489
00:23:31,309 --> 00:23:33,409
               ♪♪               

490
00:23:33,478 --> 00:23:36,880
    KING EVANS: No night off.   
        365 days a year.        

491
00:23:36,948 --> 00:23:41,551
  Some days we didn't even get  
    a chance to go to sleep.    

492
00:23:41,620 --> 00:23:46,556
           ♪<i> I've got</i>           
     <i> a sweet little angel</i> ♪    

493
00:23:46,625 --> 00:23:50,493
        ♪<i> I love the way</i>        
    <i> she spreads her wings</i> ♪    

494
00:23:50,562 --> 00:23:51,861
     KING EVANS: He told me     

495
00:23:51,930 --> 00:23:54,430
  he wasn't going to ask my mom 
         to get married         

496
00:23:54,499 --> 00:23:56,799
         because he felt        
     that she would say no,     

497
00:23:56,868 --> 00:23:58,401
    and he didn't want that.    

498
00:23:58,470 --> 00:24:01,671
 So he said, "We'll just have to
     wait until you get 18."    

499
00:24:01,740 --> 00:24:05,975
       So I said, "Okay,"       
     and that's what we did.    

500
00:24:06,044 --> 00:24:09,312
      And he was in Detroit     
          at the time.          

501
00:24:09,381 --> 00:24:12,882
  Actually, I was 18 in March,  

502
00:24:12,951 --> 00:24:15,785
    but he wanted to put off    
   getting married until June   

503
00:24:15,854 --> 00:24:17,186
     when we were in Detroit    

504
00:24:17,255 --> 00:24:19,088
        because he wanted       
       Reverend Franklin,       

505
00:24:19,157 --> 00:24:23,092
    who was Aretha Franklin's   
      father, to marry us.      

506
00:24:23,161 --> 00:24:25,695
          So we waited          
    until we got to Detroit,    

507
00:24:25,764 --> 00:24:26,996
        got the license,        

508
00:24:27,065 --> 00:24:28,798
      and Reverend Franklin     
           married us.          

509
00:24:28,867 --> 00:24:30,900
               ♪♪               

510
00:24:30,969 --> 00:24:32,435
       BONO: All I know is      

511
00:24:32,504 --> 00:24:35,972
      he he'd be a hard man     
   to have a relationship with  

512
00:24:36,041 --> 00:24:38,241
  because he's moving so fast.  

513
00:24:38,310 --> 00:24:41,811
   I mean, the dude sits down   
       when he's playing,       

514
00:24:41,880 --> 00:24:44,347
        but he is running       
        through the year.       

515
00:24:44,416 --> 00:24:46,082
           KING EVANS:          
      After we got married,     

516
00:24:46,151 --> 00:24:48,584
       we got in the car,       
       went to Cleveland,       

517
00:24:48,653 --> 00:24:49,886
        he went to work,        

518
00:24:49,955 --> 00:24:52,221
           and we just          
     kept going after that.     

519
00:24:52,290 --> 00:24:53,723
 Just one day led into another. 

520
00:24:53,792 --> 00:24:56,926
        ♪<i> Please tell me</i>        
        <i> the reason why</i> ♪       

521
00:24:56,995 --> 00:25:01,497
               ♪♪               

522
00:25:01,566 --> 00:25:03,466
   RODGERS: One of the things   
          that B.B. has         

523
00:25:03,535 --> 00:25:05,268
       is a great rapport       
  with the audience, you know,  

524
00:25:05,337 --> 00:25:07,070
   I mean, he did that song --  

525
00:25:07,138 --> 00:25:11,407
         ♪ I bought you         
       a brand-new Ford ♪       

526
00:25:11,476 --> 00:25:13,743
  ♪ And you wanted a Cadillac ♪ 

527
00:25:13,812 --> 00:25:16,913
  ♪<i> I bought you a $10 dinner</i> ♪ 

528
00:25:18,650 --> 00:25:20,717
           ♪<i> You said,</i>          
    <i> "Thanks for the snack"</i> ♪   

529
00:25:21,987 --> 00:25:24,087
        ♪ I let you stay        
        in my penthouse ♪       

530
00:25:24,155 --> 00:25:27,090
         ♪ and you said         
     it was just a shack. ♪     

531
00:25:27,158 --> 00:25:29,759
  ♪ I gave you seven children ♪ 

532
00:25:29,828 --> 00:25:32,762
      ♪ And now you want to     
         give 'em back ♪        

533
00:25:32,831 --> 00:25:34,731
      ♪<i> And now you want to</i>     
        <i> give them back</i> ♪       

534
00:25:34,799 --> 00:25:38,634
        ♪<i> Yes, I've been</i>        
      <i> down-hearted, baby</i> ♪     

535
00:25:38,703 --> 00:25:40,436
  SANTANA: If you want to hear  
           B.B. King,           

536
00:25:40,505 --> 00:25:43,639
     the crème de la crème,     
  like Dexter Gordon would say, 

537
00:25:43,708 --> 00:25:45,742
           "Listen to           
      "Live at the Regal,"      

538
00:25:45,810 --> 00:25:48,177
   and every note, every word,  
           every song,          

539
00:25:48,246 --> 00:25:52,782
    everything is a perfect,    
        flawless diamond.       

540
00:25:52,851 --> 00:25:55,618
 TROUT: All of us in this genre 

541
00:25:55,687 --> 00:25:59,389
          or all of us          
   in any kind of roots music,  

542
00:25:59,457 --> 00:26:02,291
  we take what came before us.  

543
00:26:02,360 --> 00:26:04,560
   KING: One of my favorites,   
         real favorites,        

544
00:26:04,629 --> 00:26:06,896
      was Django Reinhardt.     

545
00:26:06,965 --> 00:26:08,931
               ♪♪               

546
00:26:16,708 --> 00:26:18,975
        TRUCKS: The last        
    two or three generations    

547
00:26:19,043 --> 00:26:21,077
    are all students of B.B.    

548
00:26:21,146 --> 00:26:23,846
Everybody from B.B.'s generation
   are all students of T-Bone.  

549
00:26:23,915 --> 00:26:26,115
 I mean, he really was the guy, 
            you know?           

550
00:26:26,184 --> 00:26:29,352
KING: Well just before I went in
  the Army, about '42, I think, 

551
00:26:29,420 --> 00:26:31,988
     I heard of a guy called    
         T-Bone Walker.         

552
00:26:33,792 --> 00:26:35,758
         T-BONE WALKER:         
  ♪ I'm in love with a woman ♪  

553
00:26:37,962 --> 00:26:41,097
         ♪ But she's not        
        in love with me ♪       

554
00:26:41,166 --> 00:26:43,599
    KING: And I imagine today   
  if you listen to my playing,  

555
00:26:43,668 --> 00:26:45,535
    you'll hear a little bit    
         of all of them.        

556
00:26:45,603 --> 00:26:47,370
     I'm telling my secrets.    

557
00:26:47,438 --> 00:26:50,473
    But I think a little bit    
 of all of those people I liked,

558
00:26:50,542 --> 00:26:51,841
       with my own ideas,       

559
00:26:51,910 --> 00:26:55,278
      created the B.B. King     
   twangy guitar sound, maybe.  

560
00:26:55,346 --> 00:26:57,880
               ♪♪               

561
00:27:10,428 --> 00:27:11,861
     KING EVANS: It's tough     

562
00:27:11,930 --> 00:27:14,864
  because usually divorces come 
       because of cheating      

563
00:27:14,933 --> 00:27:20,236
     or you fall out of love    
   or you have money problems,  

564
00:27:20,305 --> 00:27:25,308
   and we had all those things  
      and we survived them,     

565
00:27:25,376 --> 00:27:28,578
   but the love always stayed.  

566
00:27:28,646 --> 00:27:31,214
   KING: If you're going to be  
      a traveling musician,     

567
00:27:31,282 --> 00:27:34,016
  marriage should be something  
     you wouldn't want to do    

568
00:27:34,085 --> 00:27:36,519
   until you're not traveling   
             a lot,             

569
00:27:36,588 --> 00:27:40,590
    because there's very few    
travelling musicians that I know

570
00:27:40,658 --> 00:27:44,360
       that have been able      
and successful in marriage life.

571
00:27:44,429 --> 00:27:46,796
 KING EVANS: It's very difficult
      to have a family life     

572
00:27:46,864 --> 00:27:50,466
   with someone who's working   
  on the road 365 days a year.  

573
00:27:50,535 --> 00:27:53,235
 KING: 'Cause the nice thing is 
      when you are married.     

574
00:27:53,304 --> 00:27:56,238
       The terrible thing       
   when you're being divorced.  

575
00:27:56,307 --> 00:27:58,174
           It's awful.          

576
00:27:58,242 --> 00:28:00,242
               ♪♪               

577
00:28:00,311 --> 00:28:02,845
       ♪<i> Got to go to work</i>      
         <i> this morning</i> ♪        

578
00:28:04,515 --> 00:28:07,383
          ♪<i> Seems like</i>          
      <i> everything is lost</i> ♪     

579
00:28:07,452 --> 00:28:08,718
   ♪<i> I got a cold-hearted...</i> ♪  

580
00:28:08,786 --> 00:28:11,187
   SEIDENBERG: He came to me,   
      I didn't come to him.     

581
00:28:11,255 --> 00:28:12,455
           MAN: Right.          

582
00:28:12,523 --> 00:28:14,256
           SEIDENBERG:          
    And he was brought to me    

583
00:28:14,325 --> 00:28:16,392
    because he had financial    
      problems -- big time.     

584
00:28:16,461 --> 00:28:18,594
    KING: Sid helped me out.    

585
00:28:18,663 --> 00:28:21,597
 He helped me get out of trouble
       with the government      

586
00:28:21,666 --> 00:28:23,099
     and a few other things.    

587
00:28:23,167 --> 00:28:25,601
     So I said, "Well, look,    
         you're my CPA,         

588
00:28:25,670 --> 00:28:29,138
but you've been doing everything
   that my manager should do.   

589
00:28:29,207 --> 00:28:31,107
     Well, why don't you be     
          my manager?"          

590
00:28:31,175 --> 00:28:34,577
      In fact, I asked him.     
        He didn't ask me.       

591
00:28:34,645 --> 00:28:35,911
     WINTERS: Well, I was 17    

592
00:28:35,980 --> 00:28:39,015
  at a little club in Beaumont  
        called The Raven.       

593
00:28:39,083 --> 00:28:41,384
  I had a fake I.D. and got in. 

594
00:28:41,452 --> 00:28:43,719
     KING: We were playing,     

595
00:28:43,788 --> 00:28:46,222
      and I saw these four      
      white people come in,     

596
00:28:46,290 --> 00:28:47,757
    and one was extra white.    

597
00:28:47,825 --> 00:28:49,725
         Jonny Winters.         

598
00:28:49,794 --> 00:28:51,894
    WINTERS: We were the only   
    white people in the club,   

599
00:28:51,963 --> 00:28:53,429
      and he'd been having      
          tax problems,         

600
00:28:53,498 --> 00:28:55,264
     and he thought we were     
          from the IRS          

601
00:28:55,333 --> 00:28:56,832
 come to bust him for his taxes.

602
00:28:56,901 --> 00:28:59,635
    KING: So I was so shocked   
          and surprised         

603
00:28:59,637 --> 00:29:03,639
  that it wasn't about the IRS, 

604
00:29:03,641 --> 00:29:05,641
    it took me a little while   

605
00:29:05,643 --> 00:29:08,477
     to kind of get my feet     
  back on the ground, you know? 

606
00:29:08,479 --> 00:29:11,280
    WINTERS: He kept saying,    
  "Well, we have arrangements." 

607
00:29:11,282 --> 00:29:13,182
         And I was like,        
  "I've heard all your records. 

608
00:29:13,184 --> 00:29:14,417
 I know all your arrangements." 

609
00:29:14,419 --> 00:29:17,653
 He asked to see my union card. 

610
00:29:17,722 --> 00:29:20,022
    He really checked me out.   

611
00:29:20,091 --> 00:29:23,292
     KING: I let him sit in,    
        and he was good.        

612
00:29:23,361 --> 00:29:25,528
         I'll tell you.         
          He was good.          

613
00:29:25,596 --> 00:29:27,997
            WINTERS:            
  It's just that he's a saint.  

614
00:29:28,065 --> 00:29:29,665
       He's a blues saint.      

615
00:29:31,269 --> 00:29:33,836
 CRAY: The first chance to play 
  in front of a white audience  

616
00:29:33,905 --> 00:29:36,472
           it's like,           
     "Who are these people?"    

617
00:29:36,541 --> 00:29:39,708
     KING: I'm grateful that    
 some of them seemed to like me.

618
00:29:39,777 --> 00:29:42,711
   I'm grateful because to me,  

619
00:29:42,780 --> 00:29:46,816
        it seemed to open       
       a few doors for us       

620
00:29:46,884 --> 00:29:51,187
    that seemed like they was   
    never going to be opened.   

621
00:29:51,255 --> 00:29:53,322
    So I sent my road manager   

622
00:29:53,391 --> 00:29:57,059
       and told them to go      
   and tell Bill I was there,   

623
00:29:57,128 --> 00:29:59,128
          but I thought         
     it was the wrong place,    

624
00:29:59,197 --> 00:30:00,629
   so we were going to leave.   

625
00:30:00,698 --> 00:30:03,732
      So Bill came back out     
      with the road manager     

626
00:30:03,801 --> 00:30:05,234
      and came on the bus.      

627
00:30:05,303 --> 00:30:07,469
          He said, "No,         
   you're at the right place."  

628
00:30:07,538 --> 00:30:09,772
SANTANA: I happened to be there.

629
00:30:09,841 --> 00:30:14,877
  The opening act was Otis Rush 
 and Steve Miller and B.B. King.

630
00:30:14,946 --> 00:30:17,613
       KING: And he said,       
     "Ladies and gentlemen,"    

631
00:30:17,682 --> 00:30:19,849
   and would you believe that   
       when he said that,       

632
00:30:19,917 --> 00:30:21,183
   you could hear a pin drop.   

633
00:30:21,252 --> 00:30:22,785
      He said, "I bring you     

634
00:30:22,854 --> 00:30:24,787
   the Chairman of the Board,   
           B.B. King."          

635
00:30:24,856 --> 00:30:29,558
   I've never been introduced   
   like that before or since.   

636
00:30:29,627 --> 00:30:33,662
   When he mentioned my name,   
       they all stood up.       

637
00:30:33,731 --> 00:30:38,234
    And I was so touched till   
   I cried standing up there.   

638
00:30:38,302 --> 00:30:39,969
  SANTANA: It was like watching 
          a chandelier.         

639
00:30:40,037 --> 00:30:41,904
  All I could see was his tears 

640
00:30:41,973 --> 00:30:44,039
      and the diamond ring      
         that he had --         

641
00:30:44,108 --> 00:30:46,642
       to wipe his tears.       

642
00:30:46,711 --> 00:30:49,712
 And I was still washing dishes 
          at the time.          

643
00:30:49,780 --> 00:30:51,780
    I was living with my mom.   

644
00:30:51,849 --> 00:30:55,684
   And when I saw B.B. receive  
     that kind of adulation,    

645
00:30:55,753 --> 00:30:59,355
       that kind of honor,      

646
00:30:59,423 --> 00:31:01,824
 I said, "This is what I want." 

647
00:31:01,892 --> 00:31:03,559
     KING: So I felt weird.     

648
00:31:03,628 --> 00:31:05,961
       It felt real weird.      

649
00:31:06,030 --> 00:31:08,163
          But I did it.         

650
00:31:08,232 --> 00:31:11,934
         And after that,        
  I cried back up the stairway. 

651
00:31:12,003 --> 00:31:14,536
   SEIDENBERG: It's like when   
   Nat King Cole broke through  

652
00:31:14,605 --> 00:31:15,971
     and they accepted him,     

653
00:31:16,040 --> 00:31:20,309
      so we kept doing that     
  after the initial '68 period, 

654
00:31:20,378 --> 00:31:23,078
      working The Fillmore,     
        working colleges.       

655
00:31:23,147 --> 00:31:24,713
    And then all of a sudden,   

656
00:31:24,782 --> 00:31:28,183
    we were able to book B.B.   
 into these rock 'n' roll clubs 

657
00:31:28,252 --> 00:31:32,221
 and other venues that never had
   black entertainers before.   

658
00:31:32,289 --> 00:31:35,357
    DR. JOHN: And it shifted    
    a couple of gears there,    

659
00:31:35,426 --> 00:31:36,892
          right there,          

660
00:31:36,961 --> 00:31:40,963
   and B.B. could do whatever   
    the hell he wanted to do.   

661
00:31:41,032 --> 00:31:45,701
              KING:             
  ♪ The thrill has gone away ♪  

662
00:31:45,770 --> 00:31:49,571
  ♪ You know you done me wrong, 
             baby ♪             

663
00:31:49,640 --> 00:31:54,710
   ♪ And you're gonna be sorry  
            someday ♪           

664
00:31:54,779 --> 00:31:58,514
 SZYMCZYK: I figured if I could 
   take some different players  

665
00:31:58,582 --> 00:32:01,216
    and put them around B.B.    

666
00:32:01,285 --> 00:32:03,619
       that something good      
          would happen.         

667
00:32:03,688 --> 00:32:04,787
    Very shortly after that,    

668
00:32:04,855 --> 00:32:06,488
        it was only like        
       eight months later,      

669
00:32:06,557 --> 00:32:09,992
     we were scheduled to do    
    another album and I said,   

670
00:32:10,061 --> 00:32:11,293
     "I'd like to do it all     
         with them, B."         

671
00:32:11,362 --> 00:32:14,029
         He said, "Sure,        
   let's do it all that way."   

672
00:32:14,098 --> 00:32:18,634
    And the big success that    
resulted out of the second album

673
00:32:18,702 --> 00:32:20,669
    was "The Thrill is Gone."   

674
00:32:20,738 --> 00:32:23,205
               ♪♪               

675
00:32:23,274 --> 00:32:25,607
              KING:             
     ♪ The thrill is gone ♪     

676
00:32:28,045 --> 00:32:32,648
   ♪ The thrill is gone away ♪  

677
00:32:32,716 --> 00:32:36,185
 STARR: John actually brought in
      "The Thrill Is Gone"      

678
00:32:36,253 --> 00:32:38,987
   and played it to all of us.  

679
00:32:39,056 --> 00:32:41,256
    I have that great memory    
            of that.            

680
00:32:41,325 --> 00:32:43,592
               ♪♪               

681
00:32:43,661 --> 00:32:46,929
     BIHARI: B.B. had really    
 a million-selling record then, 

