00:46:19,308 --> 00:46:24,078
 Indianola showed its gratitude 
and opened the B.B. King Museum.

947
00:46:24,146 --> 00:46:28,382
  Every year, tens of thousands 
         of people visit        

948
00:46:28,451 --> 00:46:29,950
     from all over the world    

949
00:46:30,019 --> 00:46:32,286
       to this little town      
         in Mississippi         

950
00:46:32,355 --> 00:46:35,689
  to share one of the greatest  
       journeys ever told.      

951
00:46:35,758 --> 00:46:39,460
 BONO: You know, the only person
 who doesn't think B.B.'s great 

952
00:46:39,528 --> 00:46:41,562
        is probably B.B.        

953
00:46:41,631 --> 00:46:43,130
               ♪♪               

954
00:46:43,199 --> 00:46:44,331
     [ Cheers and applause ]    

955
00:46:44,400 --> 00:46:47,768
    KING: Thank you so much.    
           Thank you.           

956
00:46:47,770 --> 00:46:50,004
      [ Cheers and applause     
           intensify ]          

957
00:46:51,707 --> 00:46:53,841
         People call me         
       King of the Blues.       

958
00:46:53,843 --> 00:46:55,676
 I've heard it many, many times.

959
00:46:55,678 --> 00:46:58,779
   Do you think I think that?   
          No, I do not.         

960
00:46:58,781 --> 00:47:02,082
 I think there's a lot of people
  that can do exactly what I do 

961
00:47:02,084 --> 00:47:04,685
        and a lot of them       
        can do it better.       

962
00:47:04,687 --> 00:47:06,153
      They're just not me.      

963
00:47:06,155 --> 00:47:10,691
       ♪ Did you ever hear      
      a church bell tone? ♪     

964
00:47:12,628 --> 00:47:16,563
           ♪ Ever hear          
      a church bell tone?       

965
00:47:16,632 --> 00:47:20,834
       ♪ Did you ever hear      
      a church bell tone? ♪     

966
00:47:20,903 --> 00:47:24,805
   ♪ Then you know that old B   
       is dead and gone ♪       

967
00:47:24,874 --> 00:47:27,541
            L. TONEY:           
  He never forgets old friends. 

968
00:47:27,610 --> 00:47:29,843
          If he's aware         
    of a situation with one,    

969
00:47:29,912 --> 00:47:32,179
  or an old band member who --  

970
00:47:32,248 --> 00:47:36,216
  He considers them all family, 
        current and past.       

971
00:47:36,285 --> 00:47:39,987
  JAMES: He cares about people. 
        He loves people.        

972
00:47:40,056 --> 00:47:41,689
  LOCKWOOD: And I think he was  

973
00:47:41,757 --> 00:47:44,058
    the most easygoing person   
          I ever seen.          

974
00:47:44,126 --> 00:47:45,659
   NEVILLE: He wanted to share  

975
00:47:45,728 --> 00:47:49,730
     his talent and his soul    
         with the world,        

976
00:47:49,799 --> 00:47:51,732
     and that's what he did.    

977
00:47:51,801 --> 00:47:55,803
 DR. JOHN: He's a one of a kind.

978
00:47:55,871 --> 00:47:57,771
             RAITT:             
    I mean, he's just like --   

979
00:47:57,840 --> 00:48:00,441
     You know? Unbelievable.    

980
00:48:00,509 --> 00:48:02,576
  WYMAN: There's only one B.B.  

981
00:48:02,645 --> 00:48:06,547
    BONO: For true greatness    
         to take place,         

982
00:48:06,615 --> 00:48:11,852
 there requires a long obedience
     in the same direction.     

983
00:48:11,921 --> 00:48:14,688
   KING: I can't tell anybody   
      what I want to hear,      

984
00:48:14,757 --> 00:48:17,858
         but I have a --        

985
00:48:17,927 --> 00:48:20,961
        I hear it myself,       
      but I can't play it.      

986
00:48:21,030 --> 00:48:24,565
        I don't know how        
    to really get it myself.    

987
00:48:24,633 --> 00:48:28,268
        I think sometimes       
      the sound that I hear     

988
00:48:28,337 --> 00:48:32,072
         has never been         
 the sound that I want to hear, 

989
00:48:32,141 --> 00:48:33,574
        if I make sense.        

990
00:48:33,642 --> 00:48:36,510
It is a little sound that I hear

991
00:48:36,579 --> 00:48:38,645
    but I can't tell anybody    
            about it.           

992
00:48:38,714 --> 00:48:43,617
        When I hear what        
 I would like to hear, if ever, 

993
00:48:43,686 --> 00:48:45,152
    I think I'd have to stop    

994
00:48:45,221 --> 00:48:48,222
 because it probably won't sound
as good as I'm thinking it will.

995
00:48:48,290 --> 00:48:49,690
           [ Laughs ]           

996
00:48:49,758 --> 00:48:53,160
       RAITT: I think that      
     as a lesson in living,     

997
00:48:53,229 --> 00:48:56,563
  you can look at B.B. and also 
learn what it's like to be a man

998
00:48:56,632 --> 00:48:59,333
    and get through all those   
     difficult times he had     

999
00:48:59,401 --> 00:49:01,802
 and come through with the heart
       that he still has.       

1000
00:49:01,871 --> 00:49:04,571
 That's no mean accomplishment. 

1001
00:49:04,640 --> 00:49:07,274
  KING: I don't think I've done 
the best that I could have done.

1002
00:49:07,343 --> 00:49:09,543
        I thought I had.        

1003
00:49:09,612 --> 00:49:14,515
 I thought that I did everything
        the best I could,       

1004
00:49:14,583 --> 00:49:17,985
      but when I look back,     
  I see there are some slacks.  

1005
00:49:18,053 --> 00:49:19,920
       You can do better.       

1006
00:49:19,989 --> 00:49:21,889
 L. TONEY: I've never told him, 

1007
00:49:21,957 --> 00:49:24,992
    but I sometimes call him    
      the father of us all,     

1008
00:49:25,060 --> 00:49:27,794
     because that's the way     
           I see him.           

1009
00:49:27,863 --> 00:49:31,031
       It's very difficult      
      to find words to say.     

1010
00:49:31,100 --> 00:49:34,601
          [ Sniffles ]          

1011
00:49:34,670 --> 00:49:37,504
           Excuse me.           

1012
00:49:37,573 --> 00:49:40,207
   MATTHEWS: He sang the blues  
    and did a great job of it   

1013
00:49:40,276 --> 00:49:42,709
   and rose to a great height,  

1014
00:49:42,778 --> 00:49:45,812
        were even invited       
     by kings and potentates    

1015
00:49:45,881 --> 00:49:47,314
       from where he was.       

1016
00:49:47,383 --> 00:49:48,916
              KING:             
  I've never met a king before, 

1017
00:49:48,984 --> 00:49:55,556
      so I'm a bit nervous      
 but also grateful, so grateful.

1018
00:49:55,624 --> 00:49:59,826
       POPE JOHN PAUL II:       
      [ Speaking Italian ]      

1019
00:49:59,895 --> 00:50:01,962
      I said, "Holy Father,     

1020
00:50:02,031 --> 00:50:04,231
   I know you're always doing   
       things for others,       

1021
00:50:04,300 --> 00:50:08,569
    so I want to do something   
     for you, Sir," I said.     

1022
00:50:08,637 --> 00:50:11,438
       "I'd like to offer       
       my guitar to you."       

1023
00:50:11,507 --> 00:50:13,807
       He took it himself.      

1024
00:50:13,876 --> 00:50:16,310
           He stepped           
    and took it from the guy,   

1025
00:50:16,378 --> 00:50:17,945
      and he smiled again.      

1026
00:50:18,013 --> 00:50:22,182
  Then he said, "Happy holidays 
  to you and your family, B.B." 

1027
00:50:22,251 --> 00:50:24,284
           Oh, my God!          

1028
00:50:24,353 --> 00:50:25,652
         He said "B.B."         

1029
00:50:25,721 --> 00:50:28,922
      ♪<i> Lead me on, Lord</i> ♪      

1030
00:50:28,991 --> 00:50:33,327
        ♪<i> To the light</i> ♪        

1031
00:50:33,395 --> 00:50:36,596
        ♪<i> Take my hand</i> ♪        

1032
00:50:36,665 --> 00:50:40,400
        ♪<i> Precious Lord</i> ♪       

1033
00:50:40,469 --> 00:50:42,202
        ♪<i> Lead me home</i> ♪        

